                                                                                                                                   Netaji error leads to protests

     OUR CORRESPONDENT
               
	Bhubaneswar, Jan. 13: A reported printing error in a compilation of Oriya test papers, published by Malhotra Book Depo (MBD), irked many students across the capital today. 
    
	Students took to the streets to protest the derogatory remarks allegedly made about freedom fighter Netaji Subhash Chandra Bose by the publication house  this despite the house apologising for their error and offering to withdraw the papers from bookstores. 
    
	Today, activists of All India Democratic Students Organisation (Aidso) staged a demonstration near the Assembly and burnt copies of Class VII test papers in which derogatory references regarding Netaji was allegedly printed. 
    
	The activists also submitted a memorandum to the government demanding stern action against the erring publication house. 
    
	Earlier, activists of Netaji Social Organisation and students of Netaji Public School burnt copies of the Malhotra Book Depos test papers which reportedly described Netaji as a bhanda jatiyatabadi neta (a fake nationalist leader).
    
	President of Netaji Social Organisation, Mohammad Zahid Khan said the error had hurt the sentiments of the people of Orissa. That such a reputed publication house had described Netaji as a fake was unbelievable  he roared. 
    
	Meanwhile, the publication house has expressed its regret for the unintentional error. Spokesperson for the house has said that the mistake was a typing error where bhala (good) had been mistakenly printed as bhanda (fake). The publishing house has already withdrawn the books containing the reference from the market.
    
	The DTP unit, where the book was published from, has been requested to dismiss the concerned employee who was probably responsible for the error, said the MBD spokesperson.
    
	Meanwhile, agitation continued. We have submitted our memorandum to the chief minister, Naveen Patnaik, and Governor M.C. Bhandare. We have demanded strict and immediate action against the publishing house for committing such a blunder, which has left an impression that the great leader was a fake, said Subashsis Das, an ABVP member. 
                                                                                
